2026-05-28 13:16:01,315 | LLM REQUEST model='meta-llama/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct' temperature=0.0 system='You are a data cleaning assistant. You translate user instructions into a JSON list of pandas-style cleaning operations. Your output must be valid JSON.\n' user='The current pandas DataFrame has these columns and dtypes:\n{\n  "index": "int64",\n  "timestamp": "datetime64[ns]",\n  "uniform": "float64",\n  "normal": "float64",\n  "exponential": "float64",\n  "gender": "object",\n  "risk_level": "category",\n  "categories": "object"\n}\n\nColumn names you are allowed to reference:\n[\'index\', \'timestamp\', \'uniform\', \'normal\', \'exponential\', \'gender\', \'risk_level\', \'categories\']\n\nSupported operations and their JSON formats:\n\\n1. drop_column\\n   Drop one or more columns.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "drop_column",\n  "params": {\n    "columns": ["col1", "col2", ...]\n  }\n}\\n\\n2. dropna\\n   Drop rows or columns with missing values.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "dropna",\n  "params": {\n    "axis": 0 or 1,                  # 0 = rows, 1 = columns\n    "subset": null or [<column names>]\n  }\n}\\n\\n3. fillna\\n   Fill missing values in a single column.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "fillna",\n  "params": {\n    "column": "<existing column name>",\n    "strategy": "mean" | "median" | "mode" | "constant",\n    "value": <constant value or null if not needed>\n  }\n}\\n\\n4. get_first_value_in_col\\n   Splits a column by a delimiter and returns only the first part of each element.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "get_first_value_in_col",\n  "params": {\n    "column": "<existing column name>",\n    "split_by": "<character to split by, e.g. \',\'>"\n  }\n}\\n\\n5. model_target\\n   Model/predict the target column. Optionally select a specific model to use from the model registry.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "model_target",\n  "params": {\n    "target": "<column name>",\n    "model": null or "<model name from model registry>"\n    "features": {<column_name>: <value>}\n  }\n}\\n\\n6. replace_value\\n   Replace one existing value with a new value in a single column.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "replace_value",\n  "params": {\n    "column": "<existing column name>",\n    "old_value": "<existing value>",\n    "new_value": "<new value>"\n  }\n}\\n\\n7. split_alphanumeric\\n   Splits a column into two new columns based on alphanumeric values.\n\nJSON format:\n{\n  "op": "split_alphanumeric",\n  "params": {\n    "column": "<existing column name>"\n  }\n}\\n\n\nModel options for predicting the target variable:\nregression:\n  - DecisionTree\n  - ElasticNet\n  - GradientBoosting\n  - Lasso\n  - LightGBM\n  - Linear\n  - RandomForest\n  - Ridge\n  - SVR\n  - XGBoost\nclassification:\n  - DecisionTree\n  - GradientBoosting\n  - LightGBM\n  - Logistic\n  - RandomForest\n  - SVC\n  - XGBoost\n\nUser instruction:\n"""fill missing uniforms with median"""\n\nInstructions for your response:\n- Use only these operations: [\'drop_column\', \'dropna\', \'fillna\', \'get_first_value_in_col\', \'model_target\', \'replace_value\', \'split_alphanumeric\']\n- Only reference columns that exist.\n- If the instruction implies multiple steps, return a JSON list with multiple operation objects.\n- You must ALWAYS return a valid JSON list. Never return explanations. If unsure, return [].\n  based on column names and types. For example, "fill missing ages" should target the "age" column.\n- If the instruction truly cannot be mapped to any supported operation, return an empty JSON list: [].\n- Respond with **only** a valid JSON list, e.g.:\n  [\n    {\n      "op": "fillna",\n      "params": {\n        "column": "age",\n        "strategy": "median",\n        "value": null\n      }\n    }\n  ]\nNo additional text or comments.\n'
